source_code.code:
class ABC { 
  class DEF { };
  static int GHI;
}

Bug.WithStack:
class ABC { 
  class DEF { };
  static int GHI;
}; 
int ABC::GHI = 77; 
int f() { 
  int value;\n"); 
  ABC::DEF * var;     // A 
  ABC::GHI * value;   // B 
}

Both lines A and B are grammatically ambiguous as both declarations and
expressions.  In order to generally resolve the ambiguities, I am resolving all
IASTName's bindings and taking the branch with the least problem count.  

If I resolve line A as an expression, I get an IProblemBinding (correctly).
If I resolve line B as a declaration, I get an ICPPField.  I would prefer an
IProblemBinding so that this works consistently.
I'm not sure if the problem is in CPPVisitor#createBinding() 
or CPPSemantics#resolveBinding().  

At what phase are you supposed to be looking @ the physical tree?
fixed.

In this case, whether or not to report a problem is decided in
CPPSemantics.postResolution.

CPPVisitor.createBinding( IASTName ) is the entry point, and the other
createBinding methods are for declarations of bindings. 
CPPSemantics.resolveBindings is for references of bindings.

Bug.WithOutStack:
class ABC { 
  class DEF { };
  static int GHI;
}; 
int ABC::GHI = 77; 
int f() { 
  int value;\n"); 
  ABC::DEF * var;     // A 
  ABC::GHI * value;   // B 
}

