source_code.code:
public class Test {
public static final boolean YES = true;
public static final boolean NO = !YES;
}

public class Test {
public static final boolean NO = !Test.YES;
public static final boolean YES = true;
}

public class T {
	static int i= value();
	static int j= i;

	static int j2= T.i;
	static int i2= value();
	
	static public void main(String[] args) {
	    System.out.println("i: " + i + ", j: " + j);
	    System.out.println("i2: " + i2 + ", j2: " + j2);
	}

	private static int value() {
		return 5;
	}
}

Bug.WithStack:
20050426

The sorter action shouldn't reorder fields when a field is initialized by an other.

see bug 36204 for more info
Another option would be to order the fields, but specify the class explicitly.
For example:

public class Test {
public static final boolean YES = true;
public static final boolean NO = !YES;
}

could be reordered as:

public class Test {
public static final boolean NO = !Test.YES;
public static final boolean YES = true;
}

This compiles fine, and I've been using it to solve sorting problems. Another
possibility would be to let sorting break the code and provide a quick fix to
add the explicit Class reference.
That's an interesting idea!
Olivier, what about having the CompilationUnitSorter to detect and fix these
cases by introducing qualification? Now that you are using the ASTrewrite this
is pretty simple and can be done in the same pass as the reordering.

It has to be noted that it is still possible that reordering changes the
semantics of your code if you use initializers with side effects (which is bad
practice as it asks for trouble).
The suggested fix is a big step forward as it avoids compile errors.

Moving to jdt.core
This feels more like some refactoring than just reordering constructs. Also
semantics are likely going to be changed.

int B = value();
int A = B;

will never be the same as:

int A = X.B;
int B = value();

Since in latter case A gets a default value instead of a computed one.

Independantly from refactoring, sorting should tolerate not altering the field
ordering.

Relying on field declaration order is common software practice. Breaking the
order for sorting concerns or so is not a good idea. I wouldn't blame users for
making these assumptions, as they are legite.

Also, our own experience is that the field names are rarely sorted
alphabetically, but rather are logically grouped.

Back to UI
Are you sure Philippe?

I tried with the following example on j2se 5.0, all fields get the same values.
But the idea to just leave fields in the defined order (without any ordering) is
also good. 

public class T {
	static int i= value();
	static int j= i;

	static int j2= T.i;
	static int i2= value();
	
	static public void main(String[] args) {
	    System.out.println("i: " + i + ", j: " + j);
	    System.out.println("i2: " + i2 + ", j2: " + j2);
	}

	private static int value() {
		return 5;
	}
}
Try forward references instead.
oops, that's what I wanted in the second example:
  -> static int j2= T.i2;
You are right. j2 will be 0.
This is out of scope for 3.1.
*** Bug 57548 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***
As of now 'LATER' and 'REMIND' resolutions are no longer supported.
Please reopen this bug if it is still valid for you.

