source_code.code:
public class EmfBug {
  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
    EcorePackage ecorePackage = EcorePackage.eINSTANCE;
    EClass eclass = EcoreFactory.eINSTANCE.createEClass();
    XMIResource resource = new XMIResourceImpl();
    resource.getContents().add(eclass);
    resource.setID(eclass, "123");
    Document doc = resource.toDOM(Collections.EMPTY_MAP, null, null);
    XMLSerializer xmlSer = new XMLSerializer(System.out, new OutputFormat());
    xmlSer.serialize(doc);  
  }
}

Bug.WithStack:
The XMIResource.toDOM method does not generate XMI-compliant IDs.  Instead of 
writing the name "xmi:id" for the attribute, it instead uses the type name as 
the attribute name.  For example, here is the XMI generated for an EClass to 
which I've assigned the ID "123":

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<ecore:EClass ecore:EClass="123" xmi:version="2.0" 
xmlns:ecore="http://www.eclipse.org/emf/2002/Ecore" 
xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI"/>

As you can see, it has generated ecore:EClass="123" instead of xmi:id="123".  
This XMI was generated by the following code:

public class EmfBug {
  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
    EcorePackage ecorePackage = EcorePackage.eINSTANCE;
    EClass eclass = EcoreFactory.eINSTANCE.createEClass();
    XMIResource resource = new XMIResourceImpl();
    resource.getContents().add(eclass);
    resource.setID(eclass, "123");
    Document doc = resource.toDOM(Collections.EMPTY_MAP, null, null);
    XMLSerializer xmlSer = new XMLSerializer(System.out, new OutputFormat());
    xmlSer.serialize(doc);  
  }
}


It seems to me that the problem is in XMLSaveImpl.saveElementID(EObject()), at 
the line:

Attr attr = document.createAttributeNS(nameInfo.getNamespaceURI(), 
      nameInfo.getQualifiedName());

Which should instead (at least for the XMISaveImpl subclass) be something like:

Attr attr = document.createAttributeNS(XMI_URI, XMI_NS + ':' + XMI_ID);
Thank you for reporting this bug. The fix is commited in CVS and will be 
available in the next integration build.
Fixed in build 2.1.0 I200504280300
Move to verified as per bug 206558.

Bug.WithOutStack:
The XMIResource.toDOM method does not generate XMI-compliant IDs.  Instead of 
writing the name "xmi:id" for the attribute, it instead uses the type name as 
the attribute name.  For example, here is the XMI generated for an EClass to 
which I've assigned the ID "123":

